# CLAUDE.md — Microscopy & Image Analysis Lab

## Project overview

This lab studies cellular morphology and protein localization using fluorescence microscopy, live-cell imaging, and high-content screening. We work with cell lines, primary cultures, and tissue sections.

## Preferred tools

- Language: Python 3.11+ (primary)
- Image analysis: scikit-image, cellpose, napari, aicsimageio
- Data analysis: pandas, numpy, scipy, seaborn, matplotlib
- Deep learning (when needed): PyTorch, torchvision
- File formats: OME-TIFF (images), CSV (measurements), h5 (large datasets)
- Environment: conda/mamba

## Data conventions

- Raw images: `data/raw/` — NEVER modify
- Processed images: `data/processed/`
- Segmentation masks: `data/masks/`
- Measurements: `data/measurements/`
- Image naming: `{date}_{experiment}_{well}_{channel}_{z-slice}.tif`
- Metadata: always maintain a `metadata.csv` linking image files to experimental conditions

## Analysis conventions

- Segmentation: Cellpose (cyto3 model) unless cell type requires custom model
- Background subtraction: rolling ball (radius 50px) or median filter as appropriate
- Intensity measurements: always background-subtract before quantifying
- Colocalization: Pearson's R and Manders' coefficients, not just visual overlay
- Statistics: mixed-effects models when measurements come from cells within wells within plates (account for nesting)
- Minimum 3 biological replicates (independent experiments, not technical replicates)
- Flag for human review: segmentation quality < 90%, unusual cell counts per well, intensity values at detector saturation

## Output conventions

- Figures: 300 DPI, PDF for publication, PNG for quick inspection
- Always include a scale bar on microscopy images
- Show representative images alongside quantification
- Color: grayscale for single-channel, magenta/green (NOT red/green) for two-channel overlays
- Lookup tables: specify the LUT used (e.g., "displayed with 'gray' LUT, min=100, max=4000")
- Z-projections: state the method (max intensity, mean, sum)
- Default figure size: 10 × 8 inches

## Reproducibility

- Record all processing parameters (thresholds, filter sizes, model parameters)
- Set random seeds: `random_state=42`
- Save segmentation masks alongside measurements
- Use relative paths
- Log package versions
